  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **unlawful** in virtually every country. It is a **criminal offense** that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from a lawful source.\n\n### Why is money laundering illegal?\n1. **Conceals criminal activity**: Money laundering often involves proceeds from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or organized crime.\n2. **Undermines financial systems**: It destabilizes economies and compromises the integrity of financial institutions.\n3. **Facilitates further crime**: Clean money can be used to fund additional illegal activities or terrorism.\n4. **Distorts economic activity**: It creates unfair competition and undermines legitimate businesses.\n\n### Legal Framework\nMost countries have laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in line with international standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. These laws require financial institutions and other entities to report suspicious transactions and implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include **heavy fines**, **asset forfeiture**, and **imprisonment**. Additionally, individuals or businesses involved in money laundering may face **reputational damage** and **loss of licenses**.\n\nIf you suspect money laundering, it\u2019s important to report it to the appropriate authorities.",
